If the level of the North-Sea was constant and the discharge from the rivers continued unvariable, and there were no other disturbing cau- seS, the water-strata throughout the whole system would arrange them- self in an unchangeable manner, dependent on the areas of the sections of the basins and the channels that‚connect them. The sp. gravity of the flowing water-strata, would then not, in my opinion, be the dri- ving force for the streams, but it would be the decisive cause of dif- ferences of level, assumed by the surface-strata all the way from Lin- desnaes to Tornea. These differences, causing the surface-stream, would of course be greater between different basins os the system, than between different points within the same basin. How great then is it possible , for these differences to be? Between the North-Sea and Bottenhaf no level can be assumed at a greater depth than 23 metres, without its being interrupted by land: hence the difference of level, due exclusively to specific gravity, between the North-Sea and the N orthern extremity of the Bothnian sea, cannot exceed 0546 metres, assuming the sp. gravities of the waters to be respectively 1.0270 and 1.003; whence we obtain for the whole distance an incline of only one in more than three millions ¹).
